text: If you guys actually listened to what McConaughey was saying, this trailer would make more sense to you and why the footage was shown.  He's basically saying that we used to be incredibly ambitious about pushing our limits involving space and travel.  That all changed (probably referencing the cutting of shuttle launches).  It's supposed to inspire us to get ambitious again so that we can do the things that are probably going to be done in this movie (i.e. traveling into deep space and through wormholes etc.).  It definitely gave me food for thought and made me want to go into space.

text: A quick rundown of the plot (from the early draft of the original script that was leaked a year ago) is that it takes place in a post-apocalyptic world following a famine that destroys most of the world's food supply (hence the corn fields in the trailer). A nearby wormhole is discovered and humanity mounts an expedition through it as a last ditch effort to save mankind.  More or less. The overall plot is phenomenal with a great 3rd act, though the script itself is a little rough around the edges. With some polish, this should be something amazing. :D
This is how a trailer is supposed to be done.

text: I like Christopher Nolans movies but if there's one thing they lack  - it's emotion. They are glossy and beautiful to look at, have great story, wonderful editing etc. but they often feel very cold. You don't really care about the characters because they  dont come across as humans - only as movie characters. It would be wonderful to see a beautiful, sweeping, epic sci-fi movie by CN that tugs at your heartstrings, makes your eyes water and shows you the beauty of the human race. One can only hope that this trailer is an indication of the tone of the Movie.

text: This Teaser gave me chills. And it's right, our destiny lies above us. Space is amazing and we need to keep exploring it and trying to discover more. I'm not one to really predict things about movies before they even come out but I don't see how this can be anything other than one of the best movies ever made. The plot sounds awesome and its Christopher Nolan. I'm aware people are entitled to their own opinion but if you think Nolan sucks you have a stupid ass opinion. I've seen some people say that Nolan sucks and they pretty much never give any good reasons why they just want attention because they think they "see" something about his movies everyone else doesn't because everyone calls his movies genius. There is a reason for that, look at The Dark Knight Trilogy, The Prestige, Inception, Memento, He is smart and great at making movies. I'm also not worried about any of the cast, even Topher Grace who I see a lot of people complaining about. I mean when he first cast Heath as the joker everyone was going insane and flipping out about how a gay cowboy could never play the Joker and then he ended up being one of the most memorable characters in film history.  TL;DR: This will be one of the greatest movies ever made.

text: Since most people didn't get what's this movie will be about - it's basically set in the times where wormholes are discovered and finally used, and a team of explorers and scientists use that to do time explorations and alternate dimensions. And what does that have to do with this teaser? See the teaser just filled with humankind pioneering achievements? That's what the film's gonna do - a story about another human pioneering achievement; the time and alternate dimension explorations, which was seen is not possible in the past.   I have a theory of how the time and alternate dimension works (because i wrote a story based on the same theme) to the story. But i only want to share it with you guys *if* many insists. Because if i did (but only if my theory is correct), i can probably guess how Mr. Nolan gonna ended it, which spoils the fun lol :)

text: “We’ve always defined ourselves by the ability to overcome the impossible and we count these moments, these moments when we dare to aim higher, To break barrier, to reach for the stars, to make the unknown… known. text: In the future, Earth has been devastated by war and famine caused by a plague that targets livestock, leaving only crops. Joseph Cooper (Matthew McConaughey) is a farmer who lives in Texas with his children, Tom and Murph, and his father-in-law, Donald, following the death of his wife. A skilled engineer, Cooper salvages spare parts of a old military drones to use on his plantation.  One day, he finds a probe that crash-lands nearby and, while trying to dismantle it, he accidentally activates a failsafe, forcing him and Murph to return the probe to a particular location near Los Angeles. There, Cooper finds an underground bunker guarded by a Marine robot, Tars, and is confronted by biologist Amelia Brand (Anne Hathaway) and her father, astrophysicist John Brand, who claims they're the remains of NASA.  John reveals that, before the war, his mentor, Ansen, found a ripple in the space-time continuum caused by the collision of a Neutron star with a black hole, on the other side of the galaxy. The only way the ripple could reach Earth is through a stable wormhole, which Ansen believed was created by aliens to help the human race. Several probes were sent through the wormhole to map out the other side, and the one that Cooper has found is the only one that returned.  John decodes the probe and finds a map of an ice-covered planet that could sustain human life, in addition to what appears to be white noise. There is a plan to launch a spaceship through the wormhole to create a human colony on the ice planet and transport as many humans as they can to the colony before the plague begins affecting the crops, leading to the extinction of the human race. Mission commander Case, another Marine robot, invites Cooper to join the crew, replacing John, who is too old to go. Cooper reluctantly agrees and leaves Tom and Murph with Donald, promising to return.  Cooper, Brand, Tars and Case board a spaceship, the Endurance, alongside two other scientists, Doyle and Roth, and go through the wormhole, in which they experience strange gravity distortions. On the other side of the galaxy, they find the ice planet, which is located between two black holes, Pantagruel and Gargantua. The Endurance uses Pantagruel to slingshot them into the ice planet, but the gravitational pull is too strong. Tars sacrifices himself to steer them in the right direction and is consumed by Gargantua. The Endurance loses contact with Earth, and Brand reveals that, due to time dilatation, five years have already passed on Earth.  The Endurance lands and the crew begins drilling through the planet's ice cap. Cooper finds a Chinese base set up years before, and learns that the human crew was killed by a radiation surge from the Neutron Star. The crew manages to break through the ice before the next surge and reaches the ecosystem underneath the ice cap. While Case, Roth and Doyle set up camp, Cooper and Brand explore the planet and acquire samples of its fractual lifeforms.  The following day, the crew finds the human colony created by the Chinese robots, and Roth retrieves a box that allows them to manipulate the planet's gravity. Case finds out that there is a third black hole between Pantagruel and Gargantua, and, every couple of years, it pushes the planet out of its orbit, causing it to be destroyed and then reassembled. The crew deduces that the robots created the box, though it appears impossible they have created it so fast, and decide to take the box back to Earth, where it can be used to save the planet.  On their way out, they are confronted by the Chinese robots, led by Liu, who refuse to allow them to leave in fear they might find "it". Case stays behind to fight them off while the crew attempts to reach the Endurance above the ice cap. However, it has been destroyed by the robots. The crew then decides to leave in a escape shuttle found in the colony. Roth stays behind to use the gravity box to propel the shuttle out of the planet, and Cooper copies its schematics into one of the probes, which the Chinese had abducted, so they can build another box on Earth. Before Roth activates the box, Case returns and reunites with the crew.  After Roth's death, the crew is betrayed by Case, who is actually Liu in disguise. The shuttle is sabotaged and begins being pulled into Pantagruel. The ice planet and the stable wormhole are destroyed, and hundreds of years pass as they near the Event Horizon. Cooper, however, manages to retrieve the coordinates of the place Liu didn't want them to find, which is located inside Gargantua. They head there and find a second stable wormhole, which they enter. It leads them to the space between Universes, where time stands still.  Cooper, Brand and Doyle spend weeks stranded there, aware that the human race has already been destroyed. Cooper and Brand fall in love. The gravity disruptions returns, and Cooper realizes they are extraterrestrial lifeforms attempting to communicate with them. The beings have created the wormholes and lead them to a base the Chinese robots have built inside the nowhere, where they spent years developing new technologies to save the planet, leading to the gravity box. Tars is there, waiting for them.  Brand and Tars decide to take one of the spaceships and go through another wormhole to explore the unknown, while Cooper and Doyle decide to attempt to travel back in time through another wormhole to before their departure. Brand gives Cooper the sample of the fractal lifeform and he promises to find her.  Cooper then realizes that the probe with the box's schematics is the probe he found in Texas, and realizes that, if they go through with their plan, they'll die. Doyle ignores him, tries anyway, and is killed. The probe reaches Earth, creating a time loop.  On Earth, the crew of the Endurance is assumed dead, and the program is shut down after John's death. Several years later, an adult Murph, who has become an engineer like his father, returns to the base to search for spare parts and finds the forgotten probe. He decodes it and finds the box's schematics, and spends the rest of his life trying to build a functional prototype.  After centuries, Cooper returns to Earth, now a barren, deserted wasteland plagued by hailstorms. He releases the fractal lifeform into the wild and awaits for dead when a spaceship descends from the sky. Cooper awakens in a massive space station near Earth, and learns that Murph managed to build the gravity box and save Earth. Cooper then reunites with an elderly Murph, who is on his deathbed, as well as Murph's children and grandchildren.  Cooper requests a spaceship to search for Brand, for is denied. He then becomes a janitor, accompanied by a robot he models after Tars. He learns that an ice cap has formed over Earth, and the fractal lifeforms have spread through the entire planet, and realizes John was right about there being a "plan". One day, Cooper and his robotic assistant steal of the spaceships and venture into the unknown to find Brand.

text: We have the capability, technology and man power to explore space, to leave our little planet and discover what's out there. We have the power to explore what's never been explored and with new technology to leave our galaxy and go beyond earth. We're just one planet in one galaxy. Astronomers find there are billions of other galaxies out there with trillions of planets. We could discover them, find life, find answers to so many questions we have.   But it seems money and greed holds us back from doing it. We'd rather play the game of power here on our little planet and kill each other in pointless wars, be distracted by media and live our lives in a little box. We are a small stage in a vast cosmic arena. Think of the endless cruelties visited by the inhabitants of one corner of this pixel on the scarcely distinguishable inhabitants of some other corner, how frequent their misunderstandings, how eager they are to kill one another, how fervent their hatreds. Think of the rivers of blood spilled by all those generals and emperors so that, in glory and triumph, they could become the momentary masters of a fraction of a dot, never becoming conscious enough on the wide scale to realize, we're all humans. We are the great cosmos, star stuff; we are the basic particles that formed this planet in the first place. We should all be on the same team.  (some quotes borrowed from Carl Sagan)

text: Interstellar is an upcoming science fiction film directed by Christopher Nolan. It features a team of space travelers who travel through a wormhole. Nolan combined his idea with an existing script by his brother Jonathan Nolan that was developed in 2007 for Paramount Pictures and producer Lynda Obst. Nolan is producing the film with Obst and Emma Thomas. Interstellar stars Matthew McConaughey, Anne Hathaway, Jessica Chastain, Bill Irwin, Ellen Burstyn, and Michael Caine.
author: Greg Kendrick

text: Synopsis  When a wormhole (which hypothetically can connect widely-separated regions of spacetime) is newly discovered, a team of explorers and scientists embark on a voyage through it to transcend previous limitations on human space travel.[1] The Hollywood Reporter said in addition to the official synopsis, "The plot is believed to involve time travel and alternate dimensions, but other details are being kept under wraps."

text: I do not know much about Nolan.... But I can tell you that this movie will be a priceless and inspiring tale. They have Dr. Kip Thorne (world's leading scientist on wormholes) as an executive producer and are basing much of the story off of his theories. How often do movie producers so much as consult a scientist to read over their scientifically inaccurate script (Prometheus/Armageddon/Star Trek etc.). Let alone hire one on as a director. As long as they do the story right and inspire a few people in this new materialistic generation to look up to the stars again, I will be proud and honored to spend my money on this movie. I also hope other producers will follow suit instead of making movie for money.

ITS GOING TO BE A GREAT MOVIE

author: Strife Lee Simpson

text: This is what modern trailers should aspire to be like. You are given a mood for the film; an inclination of what it will be like. The narration is compelling and engaging, but it doesn't give away any major details about the story, or twists in the narrative. No spoilers are witnessed. Bonus points given since the message is also quite inspiring, and chilling. Basically "you used to be awesome... remember how awesome you were... now go be awesome again"  Other trailers by contrast very often summarise the entire film that they're supposed to be advertising. They use pivotal clips from the second and third act of the film that ruin suspense and give too much information away. Knowing that certain characters make it to the third act for instance. Likely featuring explosions and dialogue that reveals exposition which shouldn't be in the trailer. Essentially losing intrigue in favour of raising spectacle.  I realise that I am comparing a "teaser" trailer here, to modern "theatrical" trailers in general. But I remember when THIS trailer would be considered a "theatrical" trailer years back, and a "teaser" would have even less information. Creating even more intrigue. It's a shame that trailer editing is such a dying art.

text: SPOILEEEEERS!!!  Want to know what's movie about. In 2014 NASA discovers some thingy, a portal to another star and sends probes there. Fast forward 50 years and McConaughey is a wise science guy relegated to being a repairman because he was born in a world that already started to degrade, we had a global war, famine and almost apocalypse and crops are going down each year. McConaughey lost wife during all that and he sees that his children are growing up in a world with no future, one of them is actually talented and likes to tinker with tech but Earth doesn't need scientists anymore, so his only option in life is to be a farmer.   Then one of the probes sent in 2014 returns and McConaughey finds it, dissects and hears that there is some signal recorded on it and the probe points to location in USA where to get it. McConaughey and his son go there and find an underground NASA base slowly falling in decline but with a rocket ready to go. They find out that this was the last big project USA had until everything went to shit and they had managed to keep the base unknown to looters and have advanced robots and shit. Now with the received probe and signal they've got, they can send a rocket out in space to investigate the far away star system and find out what is that signal and perhaps if there is a way to get at least some people off the dying Earth. McConaughey leaves his children behind and goes into space.   Then typical Nolan mindfuck starts, complemented with Avatar level and above visuals and a plot device from Haldeman's Forever War....  This was in the original script by Nolans, some might have been changed but judging by casting choices and filming locations, seems like on the whole the story stays

text: Great trailer! I can't wait to see the movie. But after reading through some of the comments here I felt like sharing some ideas about possibility of colonizing other planets.  First, if ever we are to space travel and find a suitable planet to colonize, it won't be sustainable enough for humans to live on. Just watch what happened to those alliens in 'War of the Worlds'. It would take a very very long time for us to adjust our physiology to all the micro life and other things you can't yet even think of. Untill then we would have to wear space suits all the time.   Second, on such a planet it is likely for intelligent life to already exist, and that could mean conflict. What if they said no? Would you go to war with aboriginals for the new living space?  Finally, it is far to expensive to transport people that far. That would mean you can only send a small crew of people to start a new colony. You can't possibly hope to evacuate the entire planet unless there is some kind of efficient star gate or instant teleportation technology that could be discovered.  What I am trying to say here is that people are so easily carried away with such unreal ideas before we have even learnt how to take care of Earth.

text: My boss just told me to order 2 staplers only made in India because the previous ones that we ordered were broken on delivery. I then found out that we have a stapler that is extremely high quality and durable (20 years old and hasn't broken yet) and it was made in the US. I cant order this stapler anymore because the company that manufactured them went out of business - their product rarely broke so people never had to order more for replacement. We need to stop this capitalist system of constantly profiting from business because in reality, only companies that continue to sell something, whether it's junk or something that requires constant maintenance make a profit. We need this to better equip ourselves in the harsh environment of space where we cannot risk damage to our tools and plating/outer hull to our vessels.

text: From the IMDb "Sypnosis" section. ( NOT FROM THE PLOT SECTION, FROM THE SYPNOSIS SECTION)  "In the future, Earth has been devastated by war and famine caused by a plague that targets livestock, leaving only crops. Joseph Cooper (Matthew McConaughey) is a farmer who lives in Texas with his children, Tom and Murph, and his father-in-law, Donald, following the death of his wife. A skilled engineer, Cooper salvages spare parts of an old military drone to use on his plantation.  One day, he finds a probe that crash-lands nearby and, while trying to dismantle it, he accidentally activates a failsafe, forcing him and Murph to return the probe to a particular location near Los Angeles. There, Cooper finds an underground bunker guarded by a Marine robot, Tars, and is confronted by biologist Amelia Brand (Anne Hathaway) and her father, astrophysicist John Brand, who claims they're the remains of NASA.  John reveals that, before the war, his mentor, Ansen, found a ripple in the space-time continuum caused by the collision of a Neutron star with a black hole, on the other side of the galaxy. The only way the ripple could reach Earth is through a stable wormhole, which Ansen believed was created by aliens to help the human race. Several probes were sent through the wormhole to map out the other side, and the one that Cooper has found is the only one that returned.  John decodes the probe and finds a map of an ice-covered planet that could sustain human life, in addition to what appears to be white noise. There is a plan to launch a spaceship through the wormhole to create a human colony on the ice planet and transport as many humans as they can to the colony before the plague begins affecting the crops, leading to the extinction of the human race. Mission commander Case, another Marine robot, invites Cooper to join the crew, replacing John, who is too old to go. Cooper reluctantly agrees and leaves Tom and Murph with Donald, promising to return.  Cooper, Brand, Tars and Case board a spaceship, the Endurance, alongside two other scientists, Doyle and Roth, and go through the wormhole, in which they experience strange gravity distortions. On the other side of the galaxy, they find the ice planet, which is located between two black holes, Pantagruel and Gargantua. The Endurance uses Pantagruel to slingshot them into the ice planet, but the gravitational pull is too strong. Tars sacrifices himself to steer them in the right direction and is consumed by Gargantua. The Endurance loses contact with Earth, and Brand reveals that, due to time dilatation, five years have already passed on Earth.  The Endurance lands and the crew begins drilling through the planet's ice cap. Cooper finds a Chinese base set up years before, and learns that the human crew was killed by a radiation surge from the Neutron Star. The crew manages to break through the ice before the next surge and reaches the ecosystem underneath the ice cap. While Case, Roth and Doyle set up camp, Cooper and Brand explore the planet and acquire samples of its fractual lifeforms.  The following day, the crew finds the human colony created by the Chinese robots, and Roth retrieves a box that allows them to manipulate the planet's gravity. Case finds out that there is a third black hole between Pantagruel and Gargantua, and, every couple of years, it pushes the planet out of its orbit, causing it to be destroyed and then reassembled. The crew deduces that the robots created the box, though it appears impossible they have created it so fast, and decide to take the box back to Earth, where it can be used to save the planet.  On their way out, they are confronted by the Chinese robots, led by Liu, who refuse to allow them to leave in fear they might find "it". Case stays behind to fight them off while the crew attempts to reach the Endurance above the ice cap. However, it has been destroyed by the robots. The crew then decides to leave in a escape shuttle found in the colony. Roth stays behind to use the gravity box to propel the shuttle out of the planet, and Cooper copies its schematics into one of the probes, which the Chinese had abducted, so they can build another box on Earth. Before Roth activates the box, Case returns and reunites with the crew.  After Roth's death, the crew is betrayed by Case, who is actually Liu in disguise. The shuttle is sabotaged and begins being pulled into Pantagruel. The ice planet and the stable wormhole are destroyed, and hundreds of years pass as they near the Event Horizon. Cooper, however, manages to retrieve the coordinates of the place Liu didn't want them to find, which is located inside Gargantua. They head there and find a second stable wormhole, which they enter. It leads them to the space between Universes, where time stands still.  Cooper, Brand and Doyle spend weeks stranded there, aware that the human race has already been destroyed. Cooper and Brand fall in love. The gravity disruptions returns, and Cooper realizes they are extraterrestrial lifeforms attempting to communicate with them. The beings have created the wormholes and lead them to a base the Chinese robots have built inside the nowhere, where they spent years developing new technologies to save the planet, leading to the gravity box. Tars is there, waiting for them.  Brand and Tars decide to take one of the spaceships and go through another wormhole to explore the unknown, while Cooper and Doyle decide to attempt to travel back in time through another wormhole to before their departure. Brand gives Cooper the sample of the fractal lifeform and he promises to find her.  Cooper then realizes that the probe with the box's schematics is the probe he found in Texas, and realizes that, if they go through with their plan, they'll die. Doyle ignores him, tries anyway, and is killed. The probe reaches Earth, creating a time loop.  On Earth, the crew of the Endurance is assumed dead, and the program is shut down after John's death. Several years later, an adult Murph, who has become an engineer like his father, returns to the base to search for spare parts and finds the forgotten probe. He decodes it and finds the box's schematics, and spends the rest of his life trying to build a functional prototype.  After centuries, Cooper returns to Earth, now a barren, deserted wasteland plagued by hailstorms. He releases the fractal lifeform into the wild and awaits for dead when a spaceship descends from the sky. Cooper awakens in a massive space station near Earth, and learns that Murph managed to build the gravity box and save Earth. Cooper then reunites with an elderly Murph, who is on his deathbed, as well as Murph's children and grandchildren.  Cooper requests a spaceship to search for Brand, for is denied. He then becomes a janitor, accompanied by a robot he models after Tars. He learns that an ice cap has formed over Earth, and the fractal lifeforms have spread through the entire planet, and realizes John was right about there being a "plan". One day, Cooper and his robotic assistant steal of the spaceships and venture into the unknown to find Brand who is aboard EVENT HORIZON."  No wonder good old Chris Nolan doesn't use the Internet…

text: Why do I see such vicious nationalism from all countries when I read youtube comments. Does it matter which country the people who made leaps into space came from? It reminds me of the World War 2 era in which nationalism permeated throughout many societies. Have we not grown as a species at all since then? When you think about it, that is one of the major sources of human conflict today. A ridiculous and childish attachment to the country one is born into that makes many believe that their country is "the best." As Einstein said, "Nationalism is an infantile disease. It is the measles of mankind."  How about we enjoy space achievements not for the prestige they bring to a nation, but for the adventurous exploration of the unknown that they represent. We, as a species, are intelligent enough to escape the gravitational bindings which had kept all living things restricted to the Earth for billions of years. It's truly awe-inspiring. After ions of time, we finally have the potential to explore the inconceivably vast expanse of space. Think about how much knowledge is out there in space waiting to be known and how many beautiful worlds, like Earth, waiting to be visited. When you think about our lives from this cosmic perspective, patriotism and nationalism seem to be a pathetic outmoded Earth-centered outlook. Why don't we expand our outlook, take a look at the stars, and embrace the immensity of unimaginable discoveries that lie ahead if we continue making bold reaches into space. The moment Yuri Gagarin orbited the Earth in 1961, space exploration became the responsibility of the ENTIRE human race, precisely because we are the only species on the Earth with the capability to shoot for the stars.   For anyone still reading this, thank you for that and I hope you share my enthusiasm. It pains me that humans are capable of such wonders and the general public barely even thinks about space and the larger perspective. While I'm writing this, I'm thinking about what I, as one teenager, can do to change anything. But I just realized that the internet provides a striking opportunity to make a global impact on many many people. On a whim, I am asking anyone out there if they want to join me on an intellectual revolution of some sort and try to begin an era in human history in which space becomes a central focus of our daily lives. Think about what tremendous acceleration this would give to space exploration if people across the world started supporting the exploration of space. I don't know how I would do this, but it would somehow incorporate inspiring pieces of writing or videos for the public's viewing. The world needs something like this. No, the universe needs something like this. Who's with me?

text: Thought this might help answer some peoples questions:  Interstellar is a movie by Director, Christopher Nolan (Inception, Dark Night Trilogy).  Mainly based on the scientific theories and script treatment of renowned theoretical physicist, Kip Thorne. Interstellar is set to be released in November 7, 2014.  Nolan and Emma Thomas are producing with Lynda Obst, and Jordan Goldberg is exec producing. Obst commissioned the original treatment and Steven Spielberg came aboard in 2006, when Paramount owned DreamWorks and after the filmmaker became intrigued by Caltech physicist and relativity expert Kip S. Thorne and his scientific theory that wormholes exist and can be used for time travel. Spielberg set Jonah Nolan to write the script, which made it easy for Christopher Nolan to come aboard after Spielberg left the project. The ambition is that Interstellar will depict a heroic voyage to the farthest borders of our scientific understanding.  The film is co-finaced by Paramount Pictures and Warner Bros. Entertainment. In coming to a deal with its rival studio, Warners, which maintains an overall deal with Nolan's Syncopy label, relinquished to Paramount its rights to co-finance the next Friday the 13th horror film as well as a potential future South Park movie, which are two properties that were originally owned by Paramount before being brought by Warners. Also included in the negotiations was an agreement to let Paramount co-finance a to-be-determined A-list Warners property

text: I don't exactly know why this trailer makes me cry. I know I am saddened by war, world hunger, political corruption, and social injustice; our current social ills of hollow innovations, mindless worship, superficial ambitions, and social superiority. Perhaps this trailer makes me believe that humanity is still destined for things greater than those which so morbidly depress me. Perhaps it makes me believe that the age of discovery is not behind us, that the true spark of innovation still exists somewhere, that there's still a sense of wonder to be had form out efforts. Perhaps this is why I cry, out of hope.

To exploit the public, to inject the dreaming to science-fiction That said, there were several thinsg I found funny. Biggest one was the notion of timetravel. Like gravity effects time. different dimensions...a black hole is a gateway for our dimension to communicate with other dimensions... Please. Time is a constant. It always have been and always will be. A particle with out motion will still move through time the same amount as molecule would. Or a star would move. Time is the ultimate constant, nothing can make it slower or faster. I could talk about it more, but it sounds too crazy(unproven and easly defeated by present day science) for you to care...

text: This was a great movie and very fun to watch... was on the edge of my seat a lot of the time. There were moments where I knew what was going to happen, but after seeing so many stories play out it's hard for everything to be surprising, lol. I think the only part that seemed silly to me was the assumption that a black hole's purpose was that it is to be controlled by man to transport himself to whichever specific point in time where he needs to be... so that he can "solve some problem". As if the universe would care so much that we existed, that it would place it's most powerfully devastating force within our grasp so that we could use it for something so selfish (to preserve our species). Again, just nitpicking... it was definitely worth watching... just found that funny.

In the beginning of the movie Cooper wants to handle a huge responsibility and sacrifices his Time with his children. In the end of the movie, Cooper see that he lived in another world even in the same universe.   Enjoy your moments in life (good or bad) because you only live them once. Distance between Humans can be removed. But The time you spent uselessly will not. This is what I learned from this movie.
